@node not02 "CONTENTS OF THE ISSUE 128 OF AMIGA FORMAT"

                   CONTENTS OF THE ISSUE 128 OF AMIGA FORMAT
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

These are the contents of the 128th issue of Amiga Format to be on sale
September ?th.

Features

   - The World of Amiga - Ben Vost, Simon Goodwin, Richard Drummond and Paul
     Cavanagh bring you details of what went on.

Reviews

   - Browser Preview - iBrowse and Voyager get long awaited revamps, including
     JavaScript and better HTML but they aren't ready yet. Ben Vost runs
     through how good they are right now.
   - Hypercom Cards - Simon Goodwin looks at two new Zorro-based Hypercom cards
     to see how fast a serial port (or four) they provide.
   - Extreme - Richard Drummond reviews this demo maker.
   - Power CD-ROM - Ben Vost looks at Power's latest low-cost offering. Will
     this be the CD drive that convinces you to upgrade from a floppy-only
     system at last?
   - ImageFX 4 WIP - Kermit Woodall concludes his explanation of the new
     features in his excellent image processing package.
   - Head 2 Head: Basics - Simon Goodwin compares and contrasts the various
     Basic packages that are available to the Amiga user wanting to program.

Creative

   - A Complete Beginners Guide to... the AFCD - Starting an occasional series
     of complete beginners guides, we look at the AFCD and show you how to get
     the best out of it in this four-page one-off.
   - Useful Arexx - Nick Veitch continues to inform us about the power of ARexx.
   - Program Perfection - Richard Drummond explains the niceties of organising
     your source.
   - Synth Studies - Tony Horgan talks about MIDI patch editors.
   - Banging the Metal - Simon Goodwin goes through the Amiga's palette.
   - Amiga.net - Dave Cusick explains how to set up plug-ins for browsers.

Coverdisks

   - On the floppies - NewIcons 4.6 and Astrokid, plus other bits and bobs
   - On the CD - Jim Collas' speech from WoA, an update for PPaint and GoldEd
     and about 580MB of other great stuff!
