@node not12 "EPIC ANNOUNCES BERTIE'S ANIMAL KINGDOM"

                     EPIC ANNOUNCES BERTIE'S ANIMAL KINGDOM
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

What is "Bertie's Animal Kingdom" ?

Bertie's Animal Kingdom is an Animal recognition game designed for nursery, and
pre-school children. The only requirement is that the child must have a basic
knowledge of how to use a mouse. Keyboard controls are not required, except to
enter the childs name for the hiscore table. All actions which the child does
highlight different areas of the screen in a bright colour so that they know
what they are doing if they click the mouse button on that spot.

For some younger children it may be advisable for a parent to stay with them and
monitor their progress or to help them with reading etc... All main text in the
game is displayed in a large vivid white font.

In the game the child is helped along by a cartoon character called "Bertie". He
gives them a task to perform, tells them what to do, and when the task is
complete he tells them how well they did. Each question answered correctly will
award them 1-3 gold stars which are shown at all times in the top left of the
screen. This is to encourage them to beat this score with each new attempt.

The difficulty settings

There are 3 difficulty settings which either the child can select or you can
instead. You can only choose one at the beginning of a new game. Easy, Normal,
and Hard. On Easy setting (recommended for first time players) the child will
have 5 lives and given a second chance if they make a mistake on one of the
questions - all the questions are multiple choice with either 3 or 4 possible
answers. On Normal settings, they are given 4 lives, and on Hard they are given
only 3 (and no second chance for the Hard setting).

As an incentive to choose a harder setting, the number of gold stars which
Bertie awards for each correctly answered question increase. 1 for Easy, 2 for
Normal, and 3 for Hard.

Don't worry - all the information in these sections, are displayed on screen in
an easily identifiable and simplified way.

The Games

Bertie's Animal Kingdom has many games. They are split into two halves. One set
of games is for Farmyard animals, and the other is for Wild Animals. It is
generally thought that the Farmyard animals are easier than the Wild ones. It is
possible for the child to choose to play a game from either category, but as the
games get more difficult they must be played in order.

Each game consists of 8 questions, based around the following themes: "Animal
Names", "Animal Sounds", "Animal Habitats", and "Animal Foods". There are 2
bonus games which are not part of these, which are simply a way to help the
child with what they have learnt so far.

The Animals

Each Question is based on a different animal, which is displayed in large
colourful pictures in the centre of the screen. Bertie will ask a question such
as "Ben likes to eat...?" and there will be 3 or 4 possible responses displayed
on the bottom of the screen. All the child needs to do is to move the mouse
pointer so that the one they think is right is lit up in blue, and click the
mouse.

A standard tick sign, or a cross will then inform the child whether they are
right or not. Most of the questions are also sentence builders as well, for
example if the child clicked on the picture of grass. The sentence would say
"Ben likes to eat grass." This helps them with basic writing skills as as well.

The sounds

As well as a nice jingle for a correct answer, and a sad jingle for a wrong one,
Bertie himself will speak. The sounds are not complex, and are appropriate for
the child to recognise when they are right or wrong.

The high score table

Each time a game is over, (when the child has run out of lives or completed the
last game) they have a chance to enter their name into the hiscore table, so
long as they have more gold stars than the bottom position. This is saved to
disk and can be viewed again when the computer is reset. The hiscore table
provides a way for different children to compare their scores, or for the same
child to see how they did on previous attempts.

