@node not28 "DAVE HAYNIE'S OPINION ABOUT JIM COLLAS LEAVING AMIGA"

              DAVE HAYNIE'S OPINION ABOUT JIM COLLAS LEAVING AMIGA
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

From: "Dave Haynie"

Sad to see more melodrama around the Amiga.

Clearly, there's a curse of some kind on the Amiga Technology, or at least the
name (it's unclear what Gateway's actually doing here).

Jim called me a short time after their Linux announcement, after I posted a list
of fatal multimedia flaws in Linux on an Amiga news list. He seemed quite
knowledgeable and willing to listen. And very set on introducing a new
Amiga-labelled machine that would, somehow, address the multimedia issues. This,
he insisted, by December.

And yet, he didn't sound wrong, at least based on the technology discussed. Much
of what he claimed was possible, and only possible, based on some very specific
system design issues (won't get into that here in detail). Without the proper
system, as in the original Amiga, it just wouldn't fly.

Why did he leave? I'm sure many theories will come up. My favorite at the moment
-- Applesque infighting within the ranks of the new Amiga company. There are
some rumors around the Amiga Community that flatly contradict much of what
Collas told me, and positing a much later ship date. Could just be rumors, could
also be that, in a sense, both were correct at the time, and since that can't be
sustained, his direction lost. Maybe we'll know soon (though Gateway is
traditionally tight lipped), maybe it'll be yet another sad mystery in this long
and angst-ridden tale...
