@node not29 "LAMBDA DEVELOPMENT UPDATE"

                           LAMBDA DEVELOPMENT UPDATE
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Only a month after I switched to PC I had to give up the Apollo 1260 turbo I
once borrowed from a friend for my Amiga 1200. That Amiga is now back to being
equipped with my trusty old Blizzard 1230-IV with 8 MB RAM. Practically this
means the complete end of my Amiga developments. I'll still be able to compile
Amiga stuff using a cross compiler though, once I bother to install one.

Development on the new virtual machine has finally started. Things are still on
the drawing board after an unsuccessful attempt at writing some test code first.
Most likely the virtual machine will be similar to Java and UnrealScript with
some things left out and others brought in. It is my intention to integrate the
virtual machine to the core library, so it can be used in projects other than
Lambda as well. "What other projects!?" I hear you ask. Well, when developing
something this big, it would be foolish not to make it as reusable as possible.
If things go very well, I might actually finish Lambda one day and be able to
start another project.

Any graphics or game engine development is still halted until the core library
and the virtual machine are up and running. I do have plans to support many
different levels of graphics output abstraction, including plain software
rendering, hardware assisted rasterization, and full T&L (transformation and
lighting) abstraction. This results in a scalable system which can support
simple Amiga graphics boards and things like NVidia geForce256 alike. Of course
it is the content, not the engine, which will ultimately decide whether a game
runs quickly on standard Amiga graphics boards or takes the most out of
geForce256...
