MAJOR NEWS ABOUT THE SOFTWARE OF THE CYBERSTORM AND BLIZZARD G4 BOARDS - August
04, 99:

After entering a cooperation agreement with QNX Software Systems Ltd., we are
able to ship the new CYBERSTORM and BLIZZARD G4 boards with the outstanding
operating system QNX Neutrino. As we - together with QSSL - will also make this
OS available to all users of existing first-generation, 603 and 604 based
PowerUP boards for free, it will be supported by a large number of current Amiga
developers very soon, and will be the operating system of choice for several
future stand-alone hardware products (from different vendors); thus, the
CYBERSTORM and BLIZZARD G4 boards with QNX Neutrino OS open up the path to the
future. The compatibility with existing applications under AmigaOS 3.x will be
maintained by the powerful AmigaOS Legacy Support. With this open and innovative
approach, which will also be choosen and supported by other vendors, the
CYBERSTORM and BLIZZARD G4 boards play a leading role in the introduction of a
next-generation series of systems and computers of different vendors, among them
our own AMIRAGE® K2 computer system.

WHAT DO THESE CHANGES MEAN FOR THE USERS?
It's simple: They bring you more performance, more functionality, and more
future - and all that for an even lower price as earlier announced! The
CYBERSTORM and BLIZZARD G4 boards provide the perfect start for all developers
and users into the next technology generation!

Additionally, the CYBERSTORM and BLIZZARD G4 boards are open systems, which can
also be used with different other software solutions. The integrated Flash-ROM
offers a boot select menu, from which different system software kernels can be
started from the Flash-ROM or from boot partitions on your hard disk (several
different boot kernels can be installed parallely). The programming of the
Flash-ROM as well as the other hardware functionality is documented, and this is
available to developers. That means it is easily possible to install and run
other software solutions (such as Warpup or Linux) without using or starting
from the QNX Neutrino OS which comes along with the boards.

UPDATES ON THE HARDWARE CONCEPT - August 04, 99:

A major change of the design of both boards is that we have decided not to
integrate SCSI and IEEE-1394 on the products as standard, and therefore reduce
the base prices of the products (we will make add-ons available, and have also
added other features, as you can read below). We have decided to do this, as we
found out that many customers have very different demands. For example, many
have been asking for implementation of the U2W SCSI interface ® even for the
BLIZZARD G4 board ® which is more expensive and would later also cause
significant additional cost to the user in respect to cabling and adaptors. On
the other hand, other customers may only want to connect some older legacy SCSI
devices and would be happy with a cheap 8-Bit SCSI port. Some other may not need
SCSI at all, but want to pay the lowest possible price for the step into the G4
generation. Consequently, we have decided to offer base boards without
specialized I/O functionality, but with the option for customized
configurations.

The good news is, that the CYBERSTORM G4 as well as the BLIZZARD G4 will both
have PCI slots already on board, which will allow to connect PCI add-ons
directly. In order to make the boards fit into the same Amiga systems as the
earlier CYBERSTORM PPC and BLIZZARD 603 boards, we will be using Mini-PCI
connectors, on which PCI modules in the new Mini-PCI standard can be installed.
This design allows the users to connect Mini-PCI add-on cards directly to the
CYBERSTORM G4 as well as the BLIZZARD G4, without the need to spend money for a
PCI bus expansion or to worry about mechanical integration of such a board.
Developers, as well, can easily use either common Mini-PCI cards and write
drivers for those, or quickly design new Mini-PCI cards with standard PCI chips.

Another change is the usage of standard SO-DIMMs (SDRAM) as they can be found on
modern notebooks, which also allow to design the boards in very compact form
factors, thus making the CYBERSTORM G4 fit into all A3000 and A4000 desktop and
tower models (with fully installed memory and Mini-PCI cards), and make the
BLIZZARD G4 fit into most A1200 tower cases on the market and in use. IMPORTANT
NOTE: These modules are available at similar prices compared to the standard
SDRAM DIMMs, as theya are used in many computers such as notebooks or Apple's
iMac.

As an integrated standard I/O port, the CYBERSTORM G4 as well as the BLIZZARD G4
will also have two USB ports to connect to a rapidly growing number of
inexpensive expansion devices.

EXPANSION OPTIONS - August 04, 99:

phase 5 digital products will also be offering some cost-effective MiniPCI
add-on modules. We have a number of options which add-on boards for I/O purposes
may be developed by us, and which will be quickly realized depending on the
actual demand. It may be noted that these options include those functions which
were originally considered to be on-board, and are now simply moved to an
optional MiniPCI card. The currently planned, optionally available modules
